name: NPR
text:
Modelers say there's a trend of rising coronavirus cases moving northward from Florida "up travel corridors like I-95.”

Vacation spots are starting to have some of the highest transmission rates — and rural areas are feeling the impact.
 https://t.co/TlCnFCVXgR

name: NPR
text:
RT @TEDRadioHour: How do spaces shape the human experience? In what ways do our rooms, homes, and buildings give us meaning and purpose?

On the latest #TRH, @TEDTalks speakers explore the power of the spaces we make and inhabit.
https://t.co/DGqZDK5Ieg

name: NPR
text:
A New Orleans trumpeter has created a gun-for-trumpet exchange program — called Trumpet Is My Weapon

"I had some trumpets lying around, and I know for me, the trumpet saved me," Shamarr Allen says.
https://t.co/HO7DDYuDkp

name: NPR
text:
Spain had strict lockdowns for 3 months. Now, with restrictions lifted, the country is seeing a trend similar to the U.S., with more young people catching the virus. 

91 cases have been linked to a single nightclub in Córdoba.
https://t.co/oaNKt7rJid

name: NPR
text:
NEW: President Trump now faces 3 new federal lawsuits over his memo calling to exclude unauthorized immigrants from the population count that is used to redistribute congressional seats.

A fourth suit may be coming from California's attorney general.
https://t.co/uUjtBvka1E

name: NPR
text:
President Trump signed 4 executive orders to lower drug prices, but policy experts say they'll likely offer patients only minimal relief and may take months to implement — if implemented at all.
https://t.co/p5DkuwlJAL

name: NPR
text:
A federal judge has denied the Oregon attorney general's request for a temporary restraining order against certain actions by federal officers in Portland, citing a lack of legal standing.
https://t.co/yP2HfBw7EB

name: NPR
text:
Think your quarantine home is bad? 

Two new thrillers, “Amulet” and “Relic,” feature characters' living spaces that are infected with dark spirits and become inescapable prisons. https://t.co/mnIXSSV43b

name: NPR
text:
The Justice Department has filed a motion for a restraining order to block a Seattle Police Department directive that bans officers from using "less lethal" crowd-control tools like pepper spray and blast balls.
https://t.co/zDlIvwuGE3

name: NPR
text: "Folklore," the surprise new album from @taylorswift13, tops our list of the week's best releases, along with new ones from @LupeFiasco, a 50th anniversary edition of @Roberta_Flack's debut album and more. https://t.co/wlLrC1tTsd

name: NPR
text:
As zoos across the country start to reopen, one curator says certain animals seem to have missed having people around — but not all of them.

"We haven't seen the cats get super excited about seeing people," he says. "But that's honestly to be expected."
https://t.co/lpsbiEmdr5

name: NPR
text:
It feels like a decade has passed since the start of the pandemic.  NPR’s Planet Money checks in on the people and stories they’ve covered along the way. 
https://t.co/ypdt02UrKI

name: NPR
text:
The power of workers — to negotiate for better pay, benefits and working conditions — has been in decline for decades. 

Harvard's @annastansbury talks about the drivers behind that decline — and what it means for the economy. 
https://t.co/zAt1z3b2WR

name: NPR
text:
The recession is hitting women especially hard — erasing 30 years of gender progress, according to a recent study. 

How much is childcare (or the lack thereof) impacting the recession? @samsanders @mdc @svaneksmith break down the numbers. https://t.co/3Jz2dBReSk
